RUBRIC STRUCTURE (from rubric.tsv)
- The NEE rubric only defines THREE anchor points: 0, 2, and 4
- Score 0 = none / little / no effort
- Score 2 = vague / minimal / limited
- Score 4 = extensive / full / ample and clear
- Scores 1 and 3 are NOT defined in the rubric
- Supervisors are using 1 and 3 as interpolations between anchors
- This is itself a finding: supervisors are misapplying the rubric scale
- The instrument is ordinal with three levels, not a 5-point scale

RUBRIC ELEMENTS (from rubric.tsv + BIP Process Organizer PDF)
- 7 elements total, each measuring a different aspect of the BIP
- Element 1: Leadership involvement of the principal in BIP development
- Element 2: Collaborative process and stakeholder involvement
- Element 3: Alignment of BIP objectives to CSIP district goals
- Element 4: Use of measurable baseline data
- Element 5: Use of research-based implementation strategies with citations
- Element 6: Description of monitoring process and corrective actions
- Element 7: Sharing of BIP results with staff, team, and administration
- IMPORTANT: Elements 1-5 are NOT supposed to be evaluated for new principals
  (principals not in position at time of BIP development)
  Elements 6 and 7 apply to ALL principals
- Each BIP response in the dataset corresponds to one element, not the whole document
- Element_numberX column identifies which element each row is scoring

ELEMENT SCORE DISTRIBUTION
- Element 4 has the highest rate of low scores (most verifiable element)
- Element 7 also trends lower (concrete sharing evidence required)
- Elements 1-3 trend higher (narrative, more subjective to evaluate)
- Element 6 and 7 show more score 0/2 variation than 1-3
- This is consistent with rubric design: harder elements are more concrete

