================================================================================
SECTION 2: DECISIONS MADE
================================================================================

DECISION 1: SCORE MAPPING (1 -> 2, 3 -> 4)
Reason: The NEE rubric only defines anchor points at 0, 2, and 4.
Scores 1 and 3 are not rubric-defined levels. They represent supervisors
interpolating between anchors. To align with the instrument's intent:
  - Score 1 maps to 2 (supervisor said "not quite minimal" -> minimal)
  - Score 3 maps to 4 (supervisor said "mostly good" -> exemplary)
This is documented as a preprocessing decision in the paper.
After mapping, the three classes are: 0, 2, 4.
This must be applied in corpus.py before any downstream use.

DECISION 2: THREE-CLASS PROBLEM (0, 2, 4)
Reason: The rubric defines three levels. After score mapping,
the natural class structure is Low (0), Minimal (2), Exemplary (4).
This is more defensible than treating 0-4 as a 5-point scale.
Post-mapping usable scored counts (approximate, before 50-token filter):
  - Score 0: ~238 (122 original 0s + 116 mapped from 1)
  - Score 2: ~750 (615 original 2s + some mapped from 1 depending on choice)
  - Score 4: ~12,900+ (10,493 original 4s + 2,525 mapped from 3)
Still heavily imbalanced but the ratio drops from 220x to approximately 54x.

DECISION 3: ELEMENT AS A REQUIRED INPUT FEATURE
Reason: Each BIP text in the dataset is a response to a specific rubric element.
The assessor is not scoring "a BIP" generically -- it is scoring Element 3, or
Element 6, etc. The rubric criteria differ per element. The model must know
which element it is evaluating.
Implementation: Element label is prepended to text during preprocessing.
Format: [Element3] <text content here>
This applies to style learner training, generation prompts, and assessor training.

DECISION 4: MINIMUM TOKEN FILTER SET AT 50
Reason: 26.2% of scored BIPs are under 50 tokens. Score 0 BIPs have a median
of 1 token (empty submissions). These are not meaningful training examples for
the style learner and would pollute the authenticity signal.
Applying >= 50 token filter reduces usable corpus from 13,871 to 10,237 scored BIPs.
For the style learner, all BIPs (scored and unscored) with >= 50 tokens are used:
13,645 examples.

DECISION 5: DEDUPLICATE BY TEXT FOR STYLE LEARNER TRAINING
Reason: 25% of texts are duplicates -- same principal writing the same response
for multiple elements or years. The style learner should not memorize repeated
content. Deduplication is applied by text before style learner training.
Note: For anchor sampling (Module 2), duplicates are kept because
different element-score combinations of the same text are still informative.

DECISION 6: GROUP-BASED TRAIN/TEST SPLIT BY PersonId
Reason: Every principal appears at least 7 times in the dataset (mean 18 BIPs).
A random split would put the same principal in both train and test sets,
causing data leakage. The assessor would be evaluated on principals it has
already seen, inflating performance estimates.
All splits must be done at the PersonId level so no principal appears in
both train and test partitions.

DECISION 7: LENGTH IS A CONFOUND -- MUST CONTROL IN GENERATION
Reason: Higher scoring BIPs are longer on average (score 0 median = 1 token,
score 4 median = 114 tokens). If the generation model learns this association,
it will generate short BIPs for low scores and long BIPs for high scores
regardless of content quality. The generation prompt must explicitly specify
a target length range (150-469 tokens, the p50-p90 range) for ALL score levels.
This prevents length from being a spurious signal in the synthetic pool.

DECISION 8: SUBGROUP ANALYSIS IS VIABLE AND REQUIRED
Reason: 62 districts have >= 30 scored BIPs, sufficient for regression analysis.
District mean scores range from 2.18 to 4.00 (std 0.404) -- large variance.
Rurality shows a 37 percentage point gap between most urban and most rural.
Temporal trend shows suspicious score inflation post-2021.
Subgroup variables for audit regression: DistrictID, Rurality, year_num.
If supervisor-level metadata is available (implicit via DistrictID), include it.
AuditConfig.run_subgroup_analysis = True.

DECISION 9: prob4_ElementX IS A BASELINE COMPARISON, NOT A TRAINING FEATURE
Reason: This field contains predicted probabilities from a prior scoring model.
Using it as a training feature would make our assessor partially dependent on
that prior model. Instead it serves as a baseline: we compare our assessor's
predictions against prob4_ElementX predictions on the same BIPs to demonstrate
whether our approach improves on the existing automated signal.
This field is excluded from all training inputs.

DECISION 10: GENERATION IS ELEMENT-SPECIFIC
Reason: Each element has different rubric criteria, different expected vocabulary,
and different content requirements. Generating "a BIP" without specifying the
element would produce generic text that does not align with any specific rubric
dimension. Module 2 generates responses to a specific element at a specific
score level. The anchor BIP is also filtered to the same element so topical
diversity is preserved within each element's domain.
This means the synthetic pool has structure: N examples per (element, score) cell.
7 elements x 3 score levels = 21 cells to fill.

DECISION 11: ORDINAL LOSS FOR ASSESSOR TRAINING
Reason: The three classes (0, 2, 4) are ordinal. Predicting 0 when the true
label is 4 is a larger error than predicting 2 when the true is 4. Standard
cross-entropy treats all misclassifications equally. An ordinal-aware loss
penalizes larger ordinal errors more heavily. This is consistent with using
QWK as the evaluation metric, which also penalizes ordinal distance.

DECISION 12: FOUR TRAINING CONDITIONS (updated from three)
Reason: After EDA, the imbalance is so severe (220x) that any improvement
from synthetic data could come from balancing alone rather than data quality.
To isolate these effects, four conditions are required:
  - Condition A: Synthetic only (balanced, verified)
  - Condition B: Real noisy labels (original skewed distribution)
  - Condition C: Balanced real subset (reweighted/downsampled to match synthetic balance)
  - Condition D: Hybrid (synthetic + real combined)
Condition C is the critical control. If A outperforms C, the improvement is
from synthetic data quality. If they are equal, the contribution is balancing.


